data.content:
Here's how to replace those `Assert.IsTrue` calls with proper MSTest assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0); // or CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty() in MSTest 3+

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users); // if relevant
    // For predicate checks, use:
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)); // acceptable, or loop:
    foreach (var user in users)
        Assert.IsTrue(user.IsActive, $"User {user.Name} is not active");

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key MSTest replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` or `CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty()` (v3+) |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` — gives actual value on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Contains(x))` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, x)` |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — any order
- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, element)`
- `CollectionAssert.DoesNotContain(collection, element)`
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)`

The main benefit: when a test fails, these give you **diagnostic messages** (e.g., "Expected: 3. Actual: 2") instead of just "Assert.IsTrue failed."
